		<p id=3D"fs-idm26233856">The standard deviation, <em data-effect=3D"itali=
cs">=CF=83</em>, is the same as the mean. <em data-effect=3D"italics">=CE=
=BC</em> =3D <em data-effect=3D"italics">=CF=83</em></p>
		<p id=3D"fs-idp111556368">The distribution notation is <em data-effect=3D=
"italics">X</em> ~ <em data-effect=3D"italics">Exp</em>(<em data-effect=3D"=
italics">m</em>). Therefore, <em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> ~ <em data-=
effect=3D"italics">Exp</em>(0.25).</p>
		<p class=3D"finger" id=3D"fs-idm18148336">The probability density functio=
n is <em data-effect=3D"italics">f</em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em>)=
 =3D <em data-effect=3D"italics">me</em><sup>=E2=80=93<em data-effect=3D"it=
alics">mx</em></sup>. The number <em data-effect=3D"italics">e</em> =3D 2.7=
1828182846... It is a number that is used often in mathematics. Scientific =
calculators have the key "<em data-effect=3D"italics">e<sup>x</sup></em>." =
If you enter one for <em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em>, the calculator wil=
l display the value <em data-effect=3D"italics">e</em>.</p>
		<p id=3D"fs-idm74833712">The curve is:</p>
		<p id=3D"fs-idp44233136"><em data-effect=3D"italics">f</em>(<em data-effe=
ct=3D"italics">x</em>) =3D 0.25<em data-effect=3D"italics">e</em><sup>=E2=
=80=930.25<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em></sup> where <em data-effect=3D=
"italics">x</em> is at least zero and <em data-effect=3D"italics">m</em> =
=3D 0.25.</p>
		<p id=3D"fs-idp127275616">For example, <em data-effect=3D"italics">f</em>=
(5) =3D 0.25<em data-effect=3D"italics">e</em><sup>(=E2=88=920.25)(5)</sup>=
 =3D 0.072. The probability that the postal clerk spends five minutes with =
the customers is 0.072.</p>
		<p id=3D"fs-idm23774336">The graph is as follows:</p>
		<div class=3D"os-figure">
			<figure id=3D"fs-idp49716608"><span data-alt=3D"Exponential graph with i=
ncrements of 2 from 0-20 on the x-axis of =CE=BC =3D 4 and increments of 0.=
